ğŸ’¡ What is a Logical Volume?

A Logical Volume (LV) is a flexible way to manage storage in Linux.
Itâ€™s like virtual storage blocks created on top of real hard disks.

Instead of using physical disks directly, we use LVM (Logical Volume Manager) to group them and create volumes.

ğŸ§± Think of it like this:

ğŸ§± You have 3 bricks (disks).

ğŸ§° You put them in a box (Volume Group).

ğŸ§© You divide the box into smaller sections (Logical Volumes).

Now, if you want more space, just add more bricks (disks) to the box!

ğŸ“¦ How LVM Works (Technically)
ğŸ”¹ 1. Physical Volume (PV):
Real hard disks or partitions.

Example: /dev/sda1, /dev/sdb1

ğŸ”¹ 2. Volume Group (VG):
Combines multiple physical volumes into one big pool.

Example: vg_data

ğŸ”¹ 3. Logical Volume (LV):
Virtual partitions created from the volume group.

You can format and mount these like normal partitions.

Example: /dev/vg_data/lv_docs

ğŸ” Why Use Logical Volumes?

Feature	Description

ğŸ“ Resize Anytime	Increase or decrease volume size

â• Add More Storage	Add new disks without reboot

ğŸ§ª Snapshots	Take backups without downtime

ğŸ”„ Flexibility	Better than fixed-size partitions

ğŸ§ª Simple Step-by-Step Example:

Letâ€™s say you have 2 disks: /dev/sdb1 and /dev/sdc1

Step 1: Create Physical Volumes

$ sudo pvcreate /dev/sdb1 /dev/sdc1

Step 2: Create a Volume Group

$ sudo vgcreate my_vg /dev/sdb1 /dev/sdc1

Step 3: Create a Logical Volume (e.g., 10 GB)

$ sudo lvcreate -L 10G -n my_lv my_vg

Step 4: Format the Logical Volume

$ sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/my_vg/my_lv

Step 5: Mount it

$ sudo mount /dev/my_vg/my_lv /mnt

Now, /mnt has 10GB of space using LVM!

--------------------------------
Term	Meaning
--------------------------------
PV		Physical disk
VG		Storage pool
LV	    Virtual usable space
